    # [Scene: Niko's Boatyard | Late Afternoon]

    scene bg ch7_453e40_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The steady rasp of a plane against oak, a gull calling from far off, a drain of rain starting like a quiet promise]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Soft, hopeful strings with a low, resonant cello underpinning]
    "You follow Niko without meaning to watch your feet. The boardroom’s fluorescent chill still sits in the back of your throat, like an oyster shell caught on your tongue. But here — among hulls half-finished and"
    "the smell of tar and varnish — the air is an old language you remember how to read."
    "Niko Kaur's hands are the first thing you notice: knuckled, charcoal-streaked, steady as tide-marks. They tap a bench once and gesture toward the space beside them. Their carved wooden locket catches a sliver of sun and throws it like a small promise across the plank floor."
    show niko_kaur at left:
        zoom 0.7

    niko_kaur "Sit. You'll get oil on your new jacket."
    show amina_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    amina_reyes "I haven't got anything new left to ruin."
    "You let out a breath that tastes like salt and papers."
    "Niko Kaur watches you for a long beat, the look complex—equal parts mistrust and an old, roughened affection. You know what they mean when they call you 'the scientist who talks too much to lawyers.' You"
    "also know the reason you didn't walk into a council chamber and shout is because someone has to build things that last."

    niko_kaur "So we're actually doing this, then. Not just talking about it."

    amina_reyes "Not just talking."
    "You flip open your waterproof notebook. The pages whisper under your thumb; tide gradients bloom in blue ink. 'If we start with oyster reefs at the shoals and stagger sediment traps along the flow corridors, we"
    "can—' You trace the lines. '—slow the surge, trap fine sediments, help the marsh migrate. The channels can be cleared and reshaped so fishing lanes stay viable. It's labor and timing, not permits.'"
    "Niko Kaur's jaw tenses, a map of someone used to repairing splinters and storms rather than arguing with bylaws. You sense their skepticism like the pressure before rain."

    niko_kaur "Sounds like a sermon. Who's paying for the sermon?"

    amina_reyes "We might not get money from the county. Not at first. We get elbow grease, knowledge, and people's time. We start small — bundles of eelgrass, oyster cages tied off to new pilings, crew rotations. We keep the boats moving."
    "Niko Kaur snorts softly, but the sound is lighter than a dismissal. They slide a well-worn multi-tool across the bench to you with a flat, businesslike motion."

    niko_kaur "Show me."
    "You hold the multi-tool for a second like it's a baton, an instrument to marshal a new kind of chorus. Your thumb presses the leather strap of the notebook; the friendship bracelet tucked into the spine"
    "rubs a memory against your palm, a small hot ache that steadies you instead of breaking you."

    menu:
        "Point out the most vulnerable stretch of marsh first":
            "You tap the map where the grasses thin and the channels converge. Niko frowns, tracing the line with a callused finger, and nods once. 'Okay. We shore that up, the rest follows.' The plan sharpens."
        "Start with rebuilding a single fishing lane to rally the boat crews":
            "You point to the channel by the old pier. Niko's mouth tightens, then twists into something like a smile. 'Doable. People show up when they can still fish by evening.' The idea becomes immediate and real."

    # --- merge ---
    "Niko watches your face as if trying to read tide-levels there, and you feel, for the first time since the vote, the slow unknotting of something inside you. It's small — not victory, not even a"
    "promise of it — but a spark: work you can touch, people who will come with you, a plan laid on wood and rope rather than on paper."

    niko_kaur "You know none of the kids here grew up thinking about 'sediment traps' as poetry."

    amina_reyes "Maybe we can make it poetry. Or at least practical metaphors."

    niko_kaur "You always did try to make everything sound like a lab workshop."
    "You laugh, a short, surprised sound. The laugh wedges between you like a plank, steadying the small boat of this conversation."
    "Niko Kaur reaches into a crate and tosses you a thin coil of nylon line, salt drying along its edges."

    niko_kaur "Right. We do the cages, we check currents, we train people how to seed oysters without killing their lunch. We'll need lists, shifts, a chain of folks willing to stand in a rain that isn't yet theirs."

    amina_reyes "I'll draw the schedules. I'll map tidal windows and volunteer shifts. I'll—"
    "You stop when the image rises in your head: your brother hauling sacks of seed oysters into a skiff. It is a quiet, blinding thing you haven't let yourself keep."
    "Niko Kaur watches that look, the one that folds your gaze inward."

    niko_kaur "You okay?"

    amina_reyes "I am. This—this is how I remember him. Not just the night that took him, but him lifting something heavy because it needed lifting. If we can make that count, then—"
    "You press your fingers to the notebook. The page catches, the ink smelling faintly of the field office. '—then it won't be only grief.'"
    "Niko Kaur's expression shifts—there's a tension you can't read fully, so you label it complex and let it be. They nod once, solid."

    niko_kaur "Then let's make a thing that holds."
    hide niko_kaur
    hide amina_reyes

    scene bg ch7_453e40_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Laughter, small barking instructions, the soft slap of water against a hull]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Swells into warmer strings; a quickening of hope]
    "You and Niko set to work. The drafts are rough at first: sketches on the back of plywood, nails hammered with rhythmic patience, lists shouted over the scrape of sanded timber. When you outline the idea"
    "of sediment traps, Niko interrupts with a snagged memory of an old family method for directing currents around a keel. The two languages braid — boatwright lore making sense of scientific models, and models giving structure"
    "to lore."
    show niko_kaur at left:
        zoom 0.7

    niko_kaur "If we anchor the first reef here, and angle the traps this way, the flow should drop turbidity and let the cordgrass take. You'd want more reef density in spring, right?"
    show amina_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    amina_reyes "Yes. And stagger depth. If we space them with gaps for juvenile fish and eel movement, the fishing lanes won't choke. We can use reclaimed pallets and local stone for the first frames."

    niko_kaur "Only you would say 'reclaimed pallets' and 'habitat connectivity' in the same breath."

    amina_reyes "It's called multitasking."
    "The day runs into evening and you walk the work with Niko: measuring, correcting, planning shifts. Somewhere between the sound of a plane smoothing a plank and Niko's low humming as they carve a sign, you"
    "feel the edge of something you haven't felt since leaving school: belonging more complicated than nostalgia, practical and warm and stubborn."
    # [Scene: Rooftop Community Garden / Evacuation Shelter | Evening]
    hide niko_kaur
    hide amina_reyes

    scene bg ch7_453e40_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The murmur of young voices, trowels scraping soil, the distant roll of thunder]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Gentle, uplifted piano; the cello from earlier grounding the chord progression]

    "Marina appears with a flurry of small bodies and a stack of hand-lettered signs" "SEED DAY,' 'PLANTS = FUTURE,' 'MARSH GUARDIANS."
    show marina_lopez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    marina_lopez "You made it! I told them we had the scientist in our corner and they'd stop asking me if 'science' is a person."
    show amina_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    amina_reyes "Only sometimes. Mostly I make graphs that scare people into action."

    marina_lopez "Graphs scare me, but you showed up with a toolbox and Niko, and that's half the battle."

    amina_reyes "Niko brought more than a toolbox."

    marina_lopez "No kidding. They brought stories, too. The kids love that."
    "You hand out seedlings — the cordgrass culms are small and bright in your palm, so fragile and so defiantly green against the dim sky. The kids' hands are quick and earnest; one child names a shoot 'Marisol' and you almost cry because the name sounds like a promise."

    menu:
        "Teach the kids the science behind eelgrass":
            "You squat by the raised bed and explain currents and sediment like it's a secret recipe. The children ask sharp, surprising questions. Marina beams; you feel the idea of legacy take a shape in small faces."
        "Let Marina run the planting while you organize volunteers":
            "You step back and sort names, shifts, and material lists. Marina wrangles the kids with a grin. You see roles slotting into place and feel the map of a movement drawn in tidy parcels."

    # --- merge ---
    "Multi-turn and earnest, your conversation with Marina tangles policy and practice. She speaks of the classroom — of the kids who asked if planting could be homework — while you map volunteer rotations on the back of a cereal box."
    "There's friction, too: the budget is a whisper that keeps finding its way into sentences."

    marina_lopez "How many cages can we realistically build before the storm season?"

    amina_reyes "A handful to start. Enough that the pilot shows measurable accretion in six months. We document every step — photos, sediment cores, volunteer logs. If we can show community labor gives outcomes, we can crowdsource modest funding and maybe catch a grant geared to 'community resilience.'"

    marina_lopez "And if we can't get the grant?"

    amina_reyes "We show up anyway. We use what we have. We make the case in pieces that are hard to ignore."
    "The rooftop feels like a small bastion. String lights hang, already beginning to glow, and you watch a child tuck a seedling into soil with a solemnity way too big for their hands. The sky grows"
    "grayer, the thunder nearer. Rain is coming — the sort that marks budgets as flimsy, that turns hand-painted signs into mush. A part of you counts the minutes like a tide."
    hide marina_lopez
    hide amina_reyes

    scene bg ch7_453e40_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Rain coming on stronger, first heavy drops spattering the rooftop boards]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A soft swell, resolving into a hopeful cadence]
    "You make lists, you measure, you laugh at Niko's jokes about bureaucrats, you teach a child to tie a knot so small it feels sacred. The movement — messy, hand-made, vulnerable — sews itself into the"
    "town's fabric through hands and hours. Without institutional funding, every plank and planted cordgrass is an act of fragile courage; and yet, as you stamp names into volunteer rosters, you feel a steady heat behind your"
    "ribs: purpose."
    "You think of your brother again — not in the sharpness of loss, but in the slow insistence of memory that asks you to do something lasting. The plan doesn't erase sorrow, but it gives sorrow an action."
    show niko_kaur at left:
        zoom 0.7

    niko_kaur "You look like you're going to start crying."
    show amina_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    amina_reyes "I might. Or I might start hammering. Either way, it's working."

    niko_kaur "Good. Keep both in reserve. You'll need them."
    "The rain turns the wooden walkways slick, and lights inside town blink on like small promises. The clients who poured cold certainty into the boardroom are a distant memory for the night; here, hands and rope and mud argue back."
    "You gather the community's plans into your notebook. Lists, annotated diagrams, a scrawled schedule for seed-planting days. The rooftop garden hums with the energy of people making things, and for the first time since the vote, you believe that small, steady acts can add up to something that matters."
    hide niko_kaur
    hide amina_reyes

    scene bg ch7_453e40_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Quiet hopeful chord held into a gentle silence]
    "Beyond the rooftop, the marsh breathes and waits. The storm-season calendar still looms; the need for broader support remains. But you leave the rooftop with mud on your boots and a list of names penciled into"
    "the spine of your notebook. You carry more than plans: you carry faces, promises, and a growing sense that hands can outlast a vote."
    "You stand at the edge of the rooftop, the town spread below like a stitched map. The rain has washed the air clean enough to see the faintest line where sea meets sky. For now, this"
    "is enough — work you can do, people who will turn up, a living shore that might breathe again."

    scene bg ch7_453e40_6 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The rain recedes to a soft sigh]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single rising piano motif; then a resolved, warm chord]
    "You feel the smallest spark of purpose turning into a steady ember. It will need tending. It will need more hands. It will need time."

    scene bg ch7_453e40_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Fade Out]

